Overview

This is looking at a sequencing run of single cells. This prep should have the same issues as the previous prep which we think was a problem with a large amount of free-floating RNA due to dead or dying cells from the sorting. Were looking at this data because this run should have multiple types of cells and were hoping that we can pick that out of the data before deciding to trash the whole experiment. There are three samples, H1, H2 and H3. There is some prior knowledge that the H1 sample might have some quality problems.

Barcode distribution

Well use Allons style of barcode plots so we can more clearly see the peaks. I loaded all the barcodes so the plot goes down to zero, but it takes forever to run so I just chopped off the top 100,000 like before.

> bc = read.table("cb-histogram.txt", header = FALSE, sep = "\t", nrows = 1e+05)
> bchead = head(bc, 1e+05)
> colnames(bc) = c("barcode", "count")
> allon_barcode_plot = function(bcs, sample) {
+     bcs_hist = hist(log10(bcs$count), plot = FALSE, n = 50)
+     fLog = bcs_hist$count
+     xLog = bcs_hist$mids
+     y = fLog * (10^xLog)/sum(fLog * (10^xLog))
+     print(qplot(xLog, y) + geom_point() + theme_bw() + ggtitle(sample))
+     return(data.frame(x = xLog, y = y, sample = sample))
+ }
> allon_barcode_plot(bc, "may")

We can see the same issue as before, there isnt a clean peak like we saw with the K562 cells. We eventually landed on an explanation of free floating RNA due to cells dying being the culprit.

Count based quality control

> mart = useMart(biomart = "ENSEMBL_MART_ENSEMBL", dataset = "mmusculus_gene_ensembl", 
+     host = "jul2015.archive.ensembl.org")
> conversions = getBM(attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id", "refseq_mrna", "ensembl_transcript_id", 
+     "mgi_symbol"), mart = mart)
> load_counts = function(count_file) {
+     counts = read.table(count_file, header = TRUE, sep = ",")
+     counts = counts %>% tidyr::separate(gene, into = c("transcript", "version"), 
+         sep = "\\.", fill = "right") %>% dplyr::left_join(conversions, c(transcript = "ensembl_transcript_id")) %>% 
+         dplyr::filter(mgi_symbol != "") %>% dplyr::select(-transcript, -version, 
+         -ensembl_gene_id, -refseq_mrna) %>% tidyr::gather(cell, count, -mgi_symbol) %>% 
+         dplyr::group_by(cell, mgi_symbol) %>% dplyr::summarise(counts = sum(count)) %>% 
+         tidyr::spread(cell, counts, fill = 0)
+     counts = as.data.frame(counts)
+     rownames(counts) = counts$mgi_symbol
+     counts$mgi_symbol = NULL
+     return(counts)
+ }
> counts = load_counts("may.counts")

Count based quality control

Genes Detected

Here we can see a bimodal distribution in genes detected, with some cells with a very small number of genes detected. We can see even the high end of the distribution only has a small number of genes detected < 1000.

> gd = data.frame(cell = colnames(counts), total = colSums(counts), detected = colSums(counts > 
+     0), sample = "may")
> ggplot(gd, aes(detected)) + geom_histogram() + theme_bw() + scale_x_log10()

Complexity

There are some cells that have a high number of counts but a low number of genes detected, these probably represent libraries with low complexity.

> ggplot(gd, aes(total, detected)) + geom_point() + theme_bw() + xlab("genes detected") + 
+     ylab("total counts")

Subset cells

> counts = counts[, subset(gd, detected > 500)$cell]

Well keep cells with > 500 genes detected. That leaves us with 14323 cells to consider.

Number of cells genes are expressed

Here again we can see that only a small number of genes are detected in the majority of the cells. Most genes are detected in < 100 of the cells.

> cpg = data.frame(gene = rownames(counts), total = rowSums(counts), detected = rowSums(counts > 
+     0))
> ggplot(cpg, aes(detected, total)) + geom_point() + scale_y_log10() + theme_bw()

Heatmap of top 200 expressed genes

This heatmap looks a little bit better than what we had before, but still isnt great considering these are the genes with the highest counts.

> top_200_heatmap = function(counts) {
+     counts = as.matrix(counts)
+     counts = head(counts[order(rowSums(counts), decreasing = TRUE), ], 200)
+     pheatmap(log(counts + 1), show_rownames = FALSE, show_colnames = FALSE)
+ }
> top_200_heatmap(counts)

Most variable genes

Here we take a shot at identifying the most variable genes to do PCA with, it is tough with the samples we have because they are very low counts. I dropped tfile-she cutoff to 1.5 so we could have enough variable genes to do jackStraw sampling later on.

> library(Seurat)

> counts.seurat = setup(counts.seurat, project = "counts", min.cells = 3, min.genes = 500,

> counts.seurat = mean.var.plot(counts.seurat, y.cutoff = 2, do.plot = TRUE, x.low.cutoff = 0.25,

PCA

It does kind of look like there are two populations of cells in these samples.

> counts.seurat = pca(counts.seurat, pcs.print = 3, genes.print = 5, do.print = FALSE)
> pca.plot(counts.seurat, pt.size = 2)

Projecting all of the genes and taking the top 500 genes with the highest loadings makes it look like there are three major of cells.

> counts.seurat = project.pca(counts.seurat, do.print = FALSE)
> loadings = counts.seurat@pca.x.full
> top = loadings[, 1]
> names(top) = rownames(loadings)
> top = top[order(abs(top), decreasing = TRUE)][1:500]
> pheatmap(log(counts[names(top), ] + 1), show_rownames = FALSE, show_colnames = FALSE)

Housekeeping genes

I pulled a set of housekeeping genes from Evidence Based Selection of Housekeeping Genes and converted them to human and mouse symbols.

> hk = as.character(read.table("../proximal-tubulue/metadata/hk.txt", header = FALSE)[, 
+     "V1"])
> hk = c(hk, c("Actb", "Gapdh"))
> housekeeping_heatmap = function(counts, hk) {
+     counts = counts[rownames(counts) %in% hk, ]
+     pheatmap(log(counts + 1), show_rownames = TRUE, show_colnames = FALSE)
+ }
> housekeeping_heatmap(counts, hk)

Marker genes

> proximal = c("Gpx3", "Tnip1", "Hrsp12", "Hpd", "Hao2", "Ccdc152", "Apom", "Tmem27")
> henle = c("Spp1", "Cryab", "Ctsl1", "S100a1", "S100a6", "Aqp1", "Timp3")
> distal = c("Map3k7", "Atp1a", "Wfdc2", "Dnase1", "Degs2", "Ly6i", "Ctsd", "Tmem52b")

These markers show up in our list of the 500 highest weighted genes in PC1, and they are weighted in ways we might expect. The proximal genes have positive PC1 weightings, the distal genes have negative PC1 weightings and the Henle markers are mixed in PC1 and PC2.

> inprox = top[names(top) %in% proximal]
> indist = top[names(top) %in% distal]
> inhenle = top[names(top) %in% henle]
> anno_row = data.frame(marker = "proximal", id = names(inprox))
> anno_row = rbind(anno_row, data.frame(marker = "distal", id = names(indist)))
> anno_row = rbind(anno_row, data.frame(marker = "henle", id = names(inhenle)))
> rownames(anno_row) = anno_row$id
> anno_row = anno_row[, "marker", drop = FALSE]

It looks like there could be more proximal cells than other cells based on those markers:

> marker_heatmap = function(counts, anno_row) {
+     counts = counts[rownames(anno_row), ]
+     pheatmap(log(counts + 1), show_rownames = TRUE, show_colnames = FALSE, cluster_rows = F, 
+         annotation_row = anno_row)
+ }
> marker_heatmap(counts, anno_row)

Summary

Well stop for now, but it does look like there could be different populations of cells in this dataset, despite the quality issues.
